ale","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Perschall</b>, a variant of <b>Parschall</b> (see   Parshall  ); alternatively, a variant of <b>Perschel</b>, from a pet form of <b>Persch</b>, a short form of   Berthold   or   Peter   in the border area with Czechia."],"variants":[{"name":"Parshall","meanings":["Americanized form of South German <b>Parschall</b>, a variant of <b>Parschalk</b>, a status name for a freeholder (a freeman with few service obligations), from Middle High German <i>bar</i> ‘naked’, ‘free from, apparent’ + <i>schalk</i> ‘servant, man’. See   Pershall  .","English: variant of   Pearsall  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Pershale was born in 1116, his father, William De Pershale, was 24 and his mother, Ellen Broughton, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. William De Pershale."},"et":{"1116–":"1116–Surnud","1116–Male":"1116–Surnud","1116–Female":"1116–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1092–Male":"1092–Surnud","1094–Female":"1094–Surnud","1116":"1116","1140":"1140","1094":"1094","1092":"1092"},"fi":{"1116–":"1116–Kuollut","1116–Male":"1116–Kuollut","1116–Female":"1116–Kuollut","1140–Mal